WEBVTT

00:01.335 --> 00:05.304
[ boat horn blaring,
bird squawking ]

00:15.182 --> 00:16.715
A toast.

00:18.686 --> 00:21.620
The meek may
inherit the earth,

00:21.622 --> 00:25.124
But the brave
will get the sea.

00:25.126 --> 00:27.893
Well, we've had
our differences,

00:27.895 --> 00:31.764
But we've also just taken
the haul of a lifetime.

00:31.766 --> 00:34.767
Take a night, enjoy it.

00:37.638 --> 00:39.071
[ sighs ]

00:39.073 --> 00:43.342
But remember --
keep your mouths shut.

00:43.344 --> 00:45.778
The most dangerous part
of a treasure hunt

00:45.780 --> 00:48.480
Is after you find it.

00:50.317 --> 00:52.751
Henry:<i> Every person</i>
<i>who has lived long enough</i>

00:52.753 --> 00:55.921
<i>Has something in their past</i>
<i>that must be forgotten --</i>

00:55.923 --> 00:57.423
<i>A moment when they've failed,</i>

00:57.425 --> 00:59.425
<i>Or when they simply went right</i>
<i>instead of left,</i>

00:59.427 --> 01:04.096
<i>And that simple choice changed</i>
<i>their life for the worse,</i>

01:04.098 --> 01:06.765
<i>So we cover it up and forget.</i>

01:06.767 --> 01:11.003
<i>But deep down, we know</i>
<i>it will come back to haunt us.</i>

01:13.374 --> 01:14.973
No! [ grunts ]

01:16.310 --> 01:19.378
[ eddie floyd's
"soul street" playing ]

01:21.849 --> 01:24.149
¶ sock it to me!
Sock it to me! ¶

01:24.151 --> 01:25.350
Yes!

01:25.352 --> 01:27.352
You look like a man
whose ship has just come in.

01:27.354 --> 01:29.721
The antique maps i bought
have just arrived,

01:29.723 --> 01:31.123
And i know
a very interested collector.

01:31.125 --> 01:34.960
Ah, john thomson --
excellent find.

01:34.962 --> 01:36.395
Thomson was one of
the first cartographers

01:36.397 --> 01:38.097
To favor accuracy
and detail.

01:38.099 --> 01:40.332
Over artistic flourish,
yes, henry, i know.

01:40.334 --> 01:42.668
Well, did you also know that
the thomsons and the morgans...

01:42.670 --> 01:45.337
...Had a long-standing feud
over a rocking chair,

01:45.339 --> 01:47.072
Which ended
in a bloody duel.

01:47.074 --> 01:48.941
Henry, i've been your son
for almost 70 years.

01:48.943 --> 01:50.409
I've heard
all of your stories.

01:50.411 --> 01:51.443
You're exaggerating.

01:51.445 --> 01:52.845
Oh, really?

01:52.847 --> 01:55.280
All right, you stump me.
Let's choose a category.

01:55.282 --> 01:58.350
Your notable deaths --
just name a year.

01:58.352 --> 02:00.119
Hmm, very well.

02:00.121 --> 02:01.453
1843.

02:01.455 --> 02:04.189
A powder-keg explosion
on a hudson bay company ship.

02:04.191 --> 02:06.058
Well, who could
forget that?

02:06.060 --> 02:07.726
1857.

02:07.728 --> 02:09.895
Uh...Avalanche.
Uh, your second.

02:09.897 --> 02:12.097
This time was the klondike,
i believe?

02:12.099 --> 02:14.766
It's happened, hasn't it?
I've become boring.

02:14.768 --> 02:16.068
Boring?
No, no, you're not boring.

02:16.070 --> 02:17.803
You just need some new --
[ bells jingle ]

02:17.805 --> 02:19.138
Jo!
Hey.

02:19.140 --> 02:20.405
Henry was
just telling a story.

02:20.407 --> 02:21.773
Oh, good.
Anything exciting?

02:21.775 --> 02:23.408
Apparently not.

02:23.410 --> 02:25.744
[ chuckles ] well,
i have something that
might float your boat.

02:25.746 --> 02:26.778
¶ music playing loud ¶

02:26.780 --> 02:28.914
¶ ooh ooh ¶

02:28.916 --> 02:31.950
¶ down on soul street, yeah ¶

02:31.952 --> 02:33.886
[ camera shutter clicking,
siren wailing ]

02:33.888 --> 02:37.956
Rick rasmussen, sea captain
and owner of medford maritime.

02:37.958 --> 02:41.326
His specialty -- finding
and salvaging sunken vessels.

02:41.328 --> 02:43.629
Let me guess --
the harpoon killed him.

02:43.631 --> 02:45.797
Yes,
very good, detective.

02:45.799 --> 02:48.467
You see this massive barb?

02:48.469 --> 02:52.037
Double flue style --
dates back to the early 1830s.

02:52.039 --> 02:53.939
We'll have to cut it out.

02:53.941 --> 02:55.674
If we remove it,
it'll damage the body.

02:55.676 --> 02:57.109
Surprise, surprise.

02:57.111 --> 02:59.311
Your partner knows
all about antique harpoons.

02:59.313 --> 03:00.812
Partner, huh?

03:00.814 --> 03:03.081
I guess we are partners,
aren't we?

03:03.083 --> 03:04.216
What?
Huh?

03:04.218 --> 03:05.617
Look, i-i'll hold,
you cut.

03:05.619 --> 03:09.421
Like starsky and hutch,
riggs and murtaugh.

03:09.423 --> 03:11.156
"lethal weapon"?

03:11.158 --> 03:13.325
You were right, jo.

03:13.327 --> 03:16.461
Rick rasmussen died
of exsanguination

03:16.463 --> 03:19.264
Caused by
a harpoon to the chest

03:19.266 --> 03:21.733
Sometime between midnight
and 1:00,

03:21.735 --> 03:23.135
But there's more.

03:23.137 --> 03:25.871
Subcutaneous hemorrhages,

03:25.873 --> 03:28.140
Diffused bleeding
on the epicardial fat,

03:28.142 --> 03:30.142
And bubbles
in the blood vessels --

03:30.144 --> 03:32.611
All point towards
decompression sickness.

03:32.613 --> 03:33.812
The bends?

03:33.814 --> 03:36.014
In my opinion,
captain rick rasmussen

03:36.016 --> 03:39.117
Was recently at sea,
most likely on a salvage.

03:39.119 --> 03:40.986
Question is,
what did he find?

03:40.988 --> 03:44.890
[ imitates pirate ] gold.
They found gold.

03:44.892 --> 03:46.024
Lucas, please.

03:46.026 --> 03:47.392
[ normal voice ]
oh, come on.

03:47.394 --> 03:48.493
I've been waiting all morning
for that moment.

03:48.495 --> 03:50.429
We found gold

03:50.431 --> 03:52.564
Wedged between
the captain's lower back molars,

03:52.566 --> 03:55.234
As if he'd bitten on a coin
to test its purity.

03:55.236 --> 03:59.004
[ imitates pirate ] pure gold,
24-karat, unalloyed.

03:59.006 --> 04:00.405
Lucas, please.

04:00.407 --> 04:02.307
Sorry. [ normal voice ] sorry.
[ clears throat ]

04:02.309 --> 04:04.376
Gold. Well, that's definitely
motive for murder.

04:04.378 --> 04:05.877
Now we just have to
find it.

04:05.879 --> 04:07.312
[ boat horn blares ]

04:11.185 --> 04:12.784
Medford maritime's
warehouse.

04:12.786 --> 04:14.853
This is where rick
kept everything he salvaged.

04:14.855 --> 04:17.789
Property manager said he last
saw him here a few days ago.

04:17.791 --> 04:20.692
He found all of this
in the ocean?

04:20.694 --> 04:23.929
There are an estimated 3 million
shipwrecks in the ocean.

04:23.931 --> 04:26.932
Each one
an aquatic time capsule.

04:26.934 --> 04:28.267
There.

04:28.269 --> 04:30.736
There's the recent additions.

04:42.850 --> 04:44.216
[ thunder crashes ]

04:49.423 --> 04:52.324
Oh, look at this.
Silverware, china plates.

04:53.594 --> 04:56.495
A lamp.

04:56.497 --> 05:00.365
I wonder how long it's been
since anyone's seen this.

05:03.504 --> 05:07.306
Whoa.
Are these shackles?

05:09.176 --> 05:12.077
What kind of ship
was this?

05:17.951 --> 05:22.754
<i>The empress of africa,</i>
a slave ship.

05:22.756 --> 05:25.123
Henry, how could you
possibly know that?

05:27.027 --> 05:30.295
-- Captions by vitac --

05:36.170 --> 05:37.469
This is incredible.
They found your ship.

05:37.471 --> 05:39.771
Incredible, indeed.
It makes no sense.

05:39.773 --> 05:43.241
I assumed<i> the empress</i> sank
off the caicos islands,

05:43.243 --> 05:44.876
But rick discovered
the wreck here,

05:44.878 --> 05:47.479
1,000 miles north
of where it was supposed to be.

05:47.481 --> 05:48.780
But wait a minute.
Wait a minute.

05:48.782 --> 05:50.782
H-how did it get there?
Oh, i don't know.

05:53.320 --> 05:55.654
Henry, what is it?

05:55.656 --> 05:59.257
I've thought about that night
for two centuries --

05:59.259 --> 06:01.727
Every moment, every detail.

06:01.729 --> 06:05.464
I've heard about all
of your deaths countless times

06:05.466 --> 06:07.499
From syphilis to smallpox,

06:07.501 --> 06:10.268
But getting this story out
of you is like pulling teeth.

06:10.270 --> 06:11.603
Now, what is it?

06:11.605 --> 06:12.671
There's something
you're not telling me.

06:12.673 --> 06:13.772
[ sighs ]

06:15.209 --> 06:19.277
This slave ship,
<i>the empress of africa...</i>

06:19.279 --> 06:21.413
Belonged to my family.

06:21.415 --> 06:24.683
[ thunder crashes ]

06:24.685 --> 06:26.184
[ ship creaking ]

06:34.661 --> 06:38.263
They tell me
you speak english.

06:38.999 --> 06:40.699
Uh-huh.

06:47.908 --> 06:49.341
Can i trust you?

06:53.147 --> 06:55.280
There is a key

06:55.282 --> 06:59.117
That unlocks your chains
and this door -- one key.

06:59.119 --> 07:01.286
I can get it to you.

07:01.288 --> 07:03.255
Do you understand?

07:05.292 --> 07:08.760
Tonight, unlock the others,
then this door,

07:08.762 --> 07:10.462
Then make your way
to the armory.

07:10.464 --> 07:12.831
It's just down
that passageway.

07:19.306 --> 07:20.739
Do you understand?

07:20.741 --> 07:22.974
Yes.

07:25.145 --> 07:26.678
I vowed to put an end

07:26.680 --> 07:29.214
To everything my father
had ever built.

07:29.216 --> 07:30.782
Freeing those slaves
aboard<i> the empress</i>

07:30.784 --> 07:32.417
Would have finished the job,
but i failed.

07:32.419 --> 07:33.819
I never made it back
with the key.

07:33.821 --> 07:35.754
No, no, no, henry, you can't
blame yourself for this.

07:35.756 --> 07:37.589
300 people died, abe.

07:37.591 --> 07:39.257
Their blood
is on my hands.

07:39.259 --> 07:41.526
My immortality is not
a condition, it's a curse.

07:41.528 --> 07:43.795
A curse?
Henry, you're a doctor.

07:43.797 --> 07:46.698
You're a man of science.
You don't believe in curses.

07:46.700 --> 07:49.468
I believe that 99.9%
of everything

07:49.470 --> 07:51.269
Can be explained
scientifically.

07:51.271 --> 07:54.339
There's no fate, no magic,
no curses,

07:54.341 --> 07:56.308
Except for one --
my own.

07:56.310 --> 07:57.909
Now, wait, wait.
Now, hold the phone.

07:57.911 --> 07:58.977
You said it yourself.

07:58.979 --> 08:00.879
You don't really know
what happened.

08:00.881 --> 08:03.148
How did<i> the empress</i> get to
the coast of new york, hmm?

08:03.150 --> 08:04.583
What are you suggesting?

08:04.585 --> 08:07.619
I'm suggesting that there's
more to the story.

08:07.621 --> 08:08.720
And it's time
that you found out

08:08.722 --> 08:10.388
What really happened
to that ship.

08:12.960 --> 08:15.260
Gold? What are we talking
about here, pirates?

08:15.262 --> 08:16.928
Well, it's modern salvage
and recovery,

08:16.930 --> 08:19.564
But the rules of the high seas
are still the same --

08:19.566 --> 08:20.866
Finder's keepers.

08:20.868 --> 08:22.467
So, how much
are we talking about here?

08:22.469 --> 08:24.135
Ah, forget about it, boss.
Could be in the millions.

08:24.137 --> 08:26.738
We searched rick's warehouse,
but still no sign of the gold.

08:26.740 --> 08:28.507
There's a memorial for him
tonight down by the docks.

08:28.509 --> 08:30.208
Apparently,
it is<i> the</i> place to drink

08:30.210 --> 08:31.510
If you're
a treasure hunter.

08:31.512 --> 08:34.579
Okay, guys.
Go talk to some pirates.

08:37.384 --> 08:39.584
[ bell dings ]
[ indistinct conversations ]

08:39.586 --> 08:40.385
Hey!

08:40.387 --> 08:42.387
[ conversations stop ]

08:42.389 --> 08:44.189
I know that, uh,
personality-wise,

08:44.191 --> 08:49.127
Rick fell somewhere between
a barracuda and a great white.

08:49.129 --> 08:51.196
[ laughter ]

08:51.198 --> 08:53.965
But i want to thank y'all
for coming to celebrate...

08:53.967 --> 08:57.135
A real son of a bitch.

08:57.137 --> 08:58.670
[ laughter ]
all: Hear, hear.

08:58.672 --> 09:00.639
[ slow-tempo rock music plays ]

09:02.476 --> 09:03.708
Excuse me, george speece?

09:03.710 --> 09:06.611
I'm detective martinez.
Yeah?

09:06.613 --> 09:08.747
You used to be
rick rasmussen's partner.

09:08.749 --> 09:12.617
Detective, everyone in this bar
works salvage and recovery.

09:12.619 --> 09:15.720
Most of what we find was stolen
at one time or another.

09:15.722 --> 09:18.557
I'm sorry.
We don't talk to cops.

09:20.761 --> 09:23.061
Let me guess --
he doesn't talk to cops.
Yeah.

09:23.063 --> 09:25.063
Yeah, i got that
from half the people in here.

09:25.065 --> 09:27.832
Other half don't know anything.
We're wasting our time, jo.

09:27.834 --> 09:29.834
Just because
people aren't talking

09:29.836 --> 09:32.137
Doesn't mean we can't find out
who was on that ship.

09:32.139 --> 09:33.371
What do you see, henry?

09:33.373 --> 09:35.507
The young man
sitting at the bar.

09:35.509 --> 09:38.109
His hands, to be precise.

09:38.111 --> 09:39.511
Those jellyfish stings

09:39.513 --> 09:42.380
Match exactly the ones
we found on rick's body.

09:42.382 --> 09:43.848
He was on the ship.

09:43.850 --> 09:45.550
Yeah, maybe, but that doesn't
mean he killed --

09:45.552 --> 09:47.152
Henry? Wh--
excuse me, sir.

09:47.154 --> 09:50.055
We're investigating the murder
of captain rick rasmussen.

09:50.057 --> 09:52.123
We wondered if we could
ask you some questions.

09:52.125 --> 09:53.658
Yeah, i'm sorry.
I don't really know anything.

09:53.660 --> 09:55.760
Oh, i do apologize.
I didn't ask your name.

09:55.762 --> 09:57.896
It's...
Davey,
but i don't really --

09:57.898 --> 10:00.498
Davey, you're here
at rick's memorial.

10:00.500 --> 10:01.833
Surely you can tell us
something.

10:01.835 --> 10:04.402
Listen, where i work,
we don't --

10:04.404 --> 10:05.637
No, of course,
you don't talk to cops.

10:05.639 --> 10:07.806
We understand.
Can i ask you something?

10:07.808 --> 10:10.709
How did rick find
the slave ship?

10:10.711 --> 10:13.945
I wasn't on rick's ship.

10:15.849 --> 10:17.916
Henry, what the hell
are you doing?

10:17.918 --> 10:20.652
Notice the largish gentleman
near the door

10:20.654 --> 10:23.054
With the second-degree burns
to his face.

10:23.056 --> 10:25.757
Solar intensity
over the northwestern atlantic

10:25.759 --> 10:27.659
Was at a 12-month high
last week,

10:27.661 --> 10:29.260
And his eyes
didn't leave davey

10:29.262 --> 10:31.730
From the moment
i started talking with him.

10:31.732 --> 10:34.599
I suggest we go outside and wait
for him and davey to leave.

10:34.601 --> 10:36.968
All right, we'll
take care of it. You stay here.

10:41.608 --> 10:44.142
Your eyes --
they're different colors.

10:44.144 --> 10:46.811
It's called heterochromia,
a genetic trait.

10:46.813 --> 10:48.346
You're full
of information.

10:48.348 --> 10:50.281
[ chuckles lightly ]
can't help it.

10:50.283 --> 10:51.816
Scotch, please.

10:59.693 --> 11:01.493
You're a diver.

11:01.495 --> 11:04.729
Diver by trade,
bartender by necessity.

11:04.731 --> 11:07.565
You have
decompression sickness,

11:07.567 --> 11:10.168
I'd say a mild case
from a recent dive.

11:10.170 --> 11:11.536
What were you after?

11:15.175 --> 11:17.742
Enjoy your drink.

11:27.220 --> 11:28.520
Let him go, chappy.

11:28.522 --> 11:30.121
Chappy:
Why'd they talk to you?

11:30.123 --> 11:31.756
You told them about the gold,
didn't you?!

11:31.758 --> 11:33.558
Davey: They already knew.
I didn't say a word, okay?!

11:33.560 --> 11:34.793
You got to believe me.

11:34.795 --> 11:36.661
Uh, excuse me?
Sorry to bother you.

11:36.663 --> 11:39.330
Which one of you murdered
rick rasmussen?

11:39.332 --> 11:40.765
Don't. He's a cop.

11:40.767 --> 11:41.900
Come on, we got to run.
Let's go.

11:41.902 --> 11:43.435
[ gun cocks ]
freeze, nypd!

11:43.437 --> 11:44.903
Mike:
On your knees, hands up!

11:44.905 --> 11:46.237
You -- you're not
going anywhere.

11:46.239 --> 11:47.772
Right there.

11:49.109 --> 11:50.508
Stay here.

11:50.510 --> 11:51.943
You know
what that means, doc?

11:51.945 --> 11:53.978
[ handcuffs click ]
don't leave the bar.

11:53.980 --> 11:56.381
He got excited.
He likes shipwrecks.

11:56.383 --> 11:59.617
Some more than others.

12:04.057 --> 12:05.790
Okay, we've got our crew --
davey, margo, and chappy.

12:05.792 --> 12:07.025
What's our working theory?

12:07.027 --> 12:08.793
They found gold
on the shipwreck.

12:08.795 --> 12:11.362
One of them got greedy,
broke into rick's office,

12:11.364 --> 12:12.430
They got in a fight...

12:12.432 --> 12:13.798
...And harpooned
our captain.

12:13.800 --> 12:15.734
Okay, let's put 'em in the box.
Hit 'em hard.

12:15.736 --> 12:18.336
Lieutenant, may i sit in
on this interrogation?

12:18.338 --> 12:21.272
I do have experience
with the nautical world.

12:24.444 --> 12:26.611
Fine.
But follow their lead.

12:27.781 --> 12:29.280
You got greedy, chappy.

12:29.282 --> 12:32.283
You got greedy, and you
killed rick for that gold.

12:32.285 --> 12:33.718
That's not true.

12:33.720 --> 12:35.820
[ inhales deeply ]
he was gonna split it with us.

12:35.822 --> 12:38.089
Mike: You don't have to split
anything if you steal it.

12:38.091 --> 12:40.725
<i>You know, i could see a big guy</i>
<i>like you handling a harpoon.</i>

12:40.727 --> 12:42.360
Why would i kill him?

12:42.362 --> 12:44.562
Rick was the only one
that knew where the gold was.

12:44.564 --> 12:46.531
Now nobody does.

12:46.533 --> 12:48.733
[ clears throat ]

12:51.104 --> 12:55.340
Mr. Chappy, how did rick find
<i>the empress of africa?</i>

12:55.342 --> 12:57.542
<i>He didn't say.</i>

12:57.544 --> 12:59.277
I didn't ask.

13:00.747 --> 13:02.380
Mike:
Davey, davey, davey.

13:02.382 --> 13:05.083
You look like a guy who's seen
his fair share of fights.

13:05.085 --> 13:07.318
Tell me --
did rick put up a good one?

13:07.320 --> 13:09.387
I didn't do it.

13:09.389 --> 13:12.390
Rick hid the gold for a reason.
He didn't trust you.

13:12.392 --> 13:14.526
He was a paranoid old man,
but he trusted me.

13:14.528 --> 13:16.561
I was the only guy
who had sailed with him before.

13:16.563 --> 13:19.731
The others -- margo, chappy --
they were the new guys.

13:19.733 --> 13:21.332
He didn't trust them.

13:21.334 --> 13:23.268
Davey, you're a diver.

13:23.270 --> 13:25.770
<i>What was the condition</i>
<i>of the shipwreck,</i>

13:25.772 --> 13:28.239
Could you tell why it sunk?

13:28.241 --> 13:30.441
No, not after 200 years.

13:31.678 --> 13:33.912
You were new
to rick's ship.

13:33.914 --> 13:37.115
Must have been tough, trying
to break into the boys' club.

13:37.117 --> 13:38.917
I could do
what any man can.

13:38.919 --> 13:40.952
Like kill one
with a harpoon?

13:40.954 --> 13:43.488
Why?

13:43.490 --> 13:45.557
Why would i?

13:45.559 --> 13:47.192
Just one question, margo.

13:47.194 --> 13:48.593
You and rick were
the deep divers.

13:48.595 --> 13:50.161
You spent time together.

13:50.163 --> 13:52.430
<i>Did he ever tell you</i>
<i>how he found the ship?</i>

13:52.432 --> 13:54.098
He had a map.

13:54.100 --> 13:57.302
A map.
Did you see it?

13:57.304 --> 13:58.803
No.

13:58.805 --> 14:01.472
He mentioned it once,
under his breath.

14:01.474 --> 14:03.208
[ pounding on glass ]

14:06.947 --> 14:08.213
Mike:
All their stories line up, boss.

14:08.215 --> 14:09.914
They found the gold,
rick hid it,

14:09.916 --> 14:11.449
And they were waiting
for his call.

14:11.451 --> 14:13.318
I think we should go back
to the warehouse

14:13.320 --> 14:15.153
And see what else
we can dig up.

14:15.155 --> 14:18.089
If i may be so bold, i'd like to
propose a new line of inquiry,

14:18.091 --> 14:21.059
Focusing on the shipwreck
and this new issue of a map.

14:21.061 --> 14:22.861
Dr. Morgan,
putting you in there

14:22.863 --> 14:24.062
Might not have been
the best idea.

14:24.064 --> 14:25.697
This is
a murder investigation.

14:25.699 --> 14:27.732
We're not looking for a map --
but the ship<i> is</i> important.

14:27.734 --> 14:29.100
We have to find out --
dr. Morgan?

14:29.102 --> 14:31.836
Thank you very much
for your help.

14:31.838 --> 14:34.405
We'll let you know
when we need you again.

14:40.313 --> 14:42.247
Henry: If there's a map,

14:42.249 --> 14:44.816
That means someone
must know about<i> the empress,</i>

14:44.818 --> 14:47.852
And now i'm forbidden
from questioning the crew.

14:47.854 --> 14:49.254
Wait a minute.
Aren't you forgetting something?

14:49.256 --> 14:52.023
Those divers brought
that ship to us.

14:52.025 --> 14:54.993
There's literally
a warehouse full of clues.

14:56.763 --> 14:58.897
Are you suggesting
that we break in

14:58.899 --> 15:00.398
And conduct
our own search?

15:00.400 --> 15:02.634
No, i'm suggesting we go
to katz's and get a sandwich,

15:02.636 --> 15:04.435
And<i> then</i> we break into
the warehouse.

15:04.437 --> 15:06.604
Never pull a job
on an empty stomach.

15:06.606 --> 15:08.473
Good point. Let's go.

15:15.015 --> 15:16.781
Abraham!
Over here.

15:16.783 --> 15:18.182
[ clears throat ]

15:18.184 --> 15:19.984
This guy, rick's,
got some incredible stuff.

15:19.986 --> 15:22.153
When's the estate sale
is what i want to know.

15:26.459 --> 15:27.458
What is that?

15:27.460 --> 15:29.594
Huh.

15:36.636 --> 15:38.870
[ grunts ]

15:41.341 --> 15:44.409
Oh, my god.

15:48.515 --> 15:50.181
Whoa.

15:55.822 --> 15:58.656
He was shot.

15:58.658 --> 16:01.626
Oh, god.
Look at those teeth.

16:04.965 --> 16:08.399
It can't be.

16:08.401 --> 16:10.301
[ door opens ]

16:10.303 --> 16:11.602
Quick.

16:24.417 --> 16:26.084
I should have brought
my gun.

16:26.086 --> 16:28.686
They're all antiques.
They wouldn't have worked.

16:30.724 --> 16:32.557
[ grunts ] damn it!

16:32.559 --> 16:35.393
[ clattering ]

16:37.330 --> 16:39.664
God,
he's trashing the place.

16:39.666 --> 16:42.166
Those are fragile artifacts.
We have to stop him.

16:42.168 --> 16:46.237
As a fragile artifact myself,
let him be.

16:48.742 --> 16:50.375
He's here illegally.

16:50.377 --> 16:52.110
So are we.

16:56.649 --> 16:58.282
Stop!

16:58.284 --> 17:00.451
No, no, no.
Henry!

17:03.523 --> 17:04.756
Nypd!

17:04.758 --> 17:06.491
Mike: Stop!

17:06.493 --> 17:08.593
Hands where
i can see 'em!

17:09.496 --> 17:10.428
Jo: Hands up!

17:10.430 --> 17:12.196
Henry?

17:14.567 --> 17:16.601
What the hell
are you doing here?

17:17.404 --> 17:18.569
Oh!

17:18.571 --> 17:20.304
I don't believe this.

17:20.306 --> 17:23.307
I'm glad we had
that sandwich first, hmm?

17:31.351 --> 17:33.418
[ indistinct conversations ]

17:35.188 --> 17:37.722
All right,
i covered for you.

17:37.724 --> 17:39.257
Reece thinks we went
to that warehouse together,

17:39.259 --> 17:41.092
And abe was omitted
from that report.

17:41.094 --> 17:42.460
Thank you.

17:42.462 --> 17:44.462
Henry, what the hell
is going on with you?

17:44.464 --> 17:46.230
What were you doing
in that warehouse?

17:46.232 --> 17:47.665
Examining the artifacts

17:47.667 --> 17:49.300
That rick recovered
from<i> the empress of africa.</i>

17:49.302 --> 17:51.369
I still believe
that hidden among them

17:51.371 --> 17:52.970
Lies the clue
to his murder.

17:52.972 --> 17:56.174
That ship has been at the bottom
of the ocean for 200 years.

17:56.176 --> 17:58.209
This is obsessive,
even for you.

17:58.211 --> 18:01.279
I prefer...Passionate
to obsessive.

18:01.281 --> 18:02.613
Your hang-up
with that ship

18:02.615 --> 18:04.816
Is deeper
than rick rasmussen's murder.

18:04.818 --> 18:07.351
What is it?

18:09.756 --> 18:11.255
[ sighs ]

18:11.257 --> 18:14.092
When<i> the empress</i>
went down,

18:14.094 --> 18:17.261
300 souls died with her.

18:17.263 --> 18:19.363
What happened aboard that ship
was a crime.

18:19.365 --> 18:21.165
Aren't we supposed
to investigate?

18:21.167 --> 18:23.434
I appreciate that,
henry.

18:23.436 --> 18:27.405
I really do, but we have
a murder to solve<i> today.</i>

18:27.407 --> 18:31.008
I need you here
in the present.

18:31.010 --> 18:34.011
You know, i admit --
you got me breaking into

18:34.013 --> 18:35.279
Rick's warehouse,
so what?

18:35.281 --> 18:38.516
Uh, it's 30 days in jail?
I'll take it.

18:38.518 --> 18:39.851
And what happens
when we test your blood

18:39.853 --> 18:42.553
Against the samples we found
on rick's body?

18:42.555 --> 18:45.623
Yeah, you know we can arrest you
on a murder charge right now?

18:47.393 --> 18:49.260
I went to see rick
'cause he owed me.

18:49.262 --> 18:51.729
We were partners,
friends before that.

18:51.731 --> 18:53.931
We found<i> the empress</i>
and decided to go after it.

18:53.933 --> 18:55.900
What happened?

18:55.902 --> 18:58.136
<i>Empress</i> was deep.

18:58.138 --> 18:59.837
We weren't equipped
for it.

19:02.175 --> 19:04.142
And then
we lost a diver.

19:04.144 --> 19:06.043
The man died.

19:06.045 --> 19:07.378
Was it rick's fault?

19:07.380 --> 19:08.946
You're damn right it was,
and i said so.

19:08.948 --> 19:11.315
Bastard thought
i'd lost my stomach for it,

19:11.317 --> 19:12.550
And he cut me out.

19:12.552 --> 19:14.585
Then you went to collect it,
rick said no,

19:14.587 --> 19:17.054
You got in a fight,
and you killed him.

19:17.056 --> 19:19.023
That makes sense.

19:19.025 --> 19:21.025
Rick and i were friends
a long time,

19:21.027 --> 19:23.427
Went on a lot of dives,

19:23.429 --> 19:26.164
Saved each other
on more than one occasion.

19:26.166 --> 19:27.632
I didn't kill
an old friend

19:27.634 --> 19:30.334
With a harpoon that we found
off montauk when we were 16.

19:30.336 --> 19:33.571
All right,
you knew where<i> the empress</i> was.

19:33.573 --> 19:36.140
Why didn't you
go after it yourself?

19:36.142 --> 19:37.608
I told you,
it was too deep.

19:37.610 --> 19:40.211
Rick had to spend millions
reoutfitting his boat.

19:40.213 --> 19:42.480
What about the gold?
I don't know.

19:42.482 --> 19:45.449
Old sea dog must have found
some financier to bankroll him,

19:45.451 --> 19:48.319
Like a wall street guy.

19:48.321 --> 19:50.922
Those are
the real pirates.

19:54.227 --> 19:55.993
[ both grunt ]

19:55.995 --> 19:57.562
[ lucas coughs ]

19:57.564 --> 19:59.330
Wow.

19:59.332 --> 20:01.032
Talk about a cold case.
Hmm.

20:01.034 --> 20:04.535
We found these remains in our
victim's warehouse last night.

20:04.537 --> 20:07.638
They were from
a 200-year-old shipwreck.

20:07.640 --> 20:09.040
Let's find out
what happened to him.

20:09.042 --> 20:10.808
200 years old.

20:10.810 --> 20:13.277
Guess there aren't any
[imitates pirate] aye-witnesses?

20:13.279 --> 20:14.712
[ chuckles ]

20:14.714 --> 20:16.347
[ normal voice ]
okay, i'm done.

20:17.550 --> 20:19.650
Looks like our subject
was murdered,

20:19.652 --> 20:21.485
Shot in the head
with a musket ball.

20:21.487 --> 20:24.322
The filed teeth implied
that he was from west africa,

20:24.324 --> 20:26.290
Therefore a slave
aboard the ship.

20:26.292 --> 20:28.926
Oh. At least they gave him
a decent burial.

20:28.928 --> 20:30.428
[ slaps box ]

20:30.430 --> 20:33.564
You're right.
Why was he in a coffin?

20:33.566 --> 20:36.367
A dead slave would have been
cast overboard,

20:36.369 --> 20:38.703
But this man
was cared for --

20:38.705 --> 20:42.340
His death treated
with dignity.

20:42.342 --> 20:45.576
[ ship creaking,
water dripping ]

21:00.260 --> 21:04.295
Dr. Morgan. A word.

21:06.733 --> 21:10.801
Something went missing,
a key.

21:10.803 --> 21:13.371
Do you know
anything about that?

21:13.373 --> 21:16.641
Of course not.
Are you accusing me?

21:19.212 --> 21:21.879
You may be
the owner's son,

21:21.881 --> 21:26.984
But out here,
i'm judge and jury.

21:26.986 --> 21:29.787
Make one wrong move...

21:29.789 --> 21:32.223
And what?

21:32.225 --> 21:34.759
Sir, we need the doctor.

21:34.761 --> 21:36.360
There's a slave
with fever.

21:36.362 --> 21:38.296
[ sighs ] damn it.

21:38.298 --> 21:40.798
Well, allow me to see him.
I can help.

21:45.238 --> 21:47.538
Remember what i said,
doctor.

21:49.375 --> 21:51.108
[ knock on door ]
jo: Henry?

21:51.110 --> 21:52.443
Are you in the present?

21:52.445 --> 21:54.378
Yes, of course.

21:54.380 --> 21:55.746
What of george speece?

21:55.748 --> 21:57.915
Well, we're still
running down his alibi,

21:57.917 --> 22:00.451
But between us,
i don't think he's our guy.

22:00.453 --> 22:03.154
He did turn us on, however,
to another suspect.

22:03.156 --> 22:04.922
Who?
A financier.

22:04.924 --> 22:06.657
Rick's bank records
confirmed

22:06.659 --> 22:08.459
That he spent
the last eight months

22:08.461 --> 22:12.430
Reoutfitting his ship
to the tune of $1.7 million.

22:14.167 --> 22:15.366
Where did that money
come from?

22:15.368 --> 22:16.867
Well,
the invoices were paid

22:16.869 --> 22:18.836
By a company called
the lagos group.

22:18.838 --> 22:20.504
It's owned
by isaac monroe.

22:20.506 --> 22:22.206
Maybe he knows
about the gold.

22:22.208 --> 22:25.309
He's giving a speech tonight
at the explorer's club.

22:25.311 --> 22:27.445
Do you know it?
Of course.

22:27.447 --> 22:28.713
Founded in 1904

22:28.715 --> 22:30.581
By adolphus greely
and marshall saville.

22:30.583 --> 22:31.916
Are you a member?

22:31.918 --> 22:35.319
I, uh, have a subscription
to their magazine.

22:35.321 --> 22:38.055
Great.
Let's go, i need you.

22:38.057 --> 22:39.323
Oh, we'll have to change.

22:39.325 --> 22:41.225
It'll likely be
a black-tie affair.

22:41.227 --> 22:43.194
Not for us.

22:43.196 --> 22:45.629
[ classical music playing ]

22:50.470 --> 22:52.169
It would have taken us
10 minutes

22:52.171 --> 22:53.604
To make ourselves
presentable.

22:53.606 --> 22:56.040
You look fine.

22:57.643 --> 23:01.345
Hey, this must be the diver
george told us about.

23:01.347 --> 23:04.482
He died on
one of rick's salvages,

23:04.484 --> 23:07.017
And that must be
our financier.

23:07.019 --> 23:08.652
Man: If everyone will please
take their seats,

23:08.654 --> 23:10.254
We are about to begin.

23:10.256 --> 23:11.789
Excuse me, mr. Monroe?

23:11.791 --> 23:14.592
I am detective martinez.
This is dr. Henry morgan.

23:14.594 --> 23:17.995
If you don't mind,
i'll be with you in a moment.

23:17.997 --> 23:20.898
Wait, we're investigating
rick rasmussen's murder.

23:20.900 --> 23:22.566
We believe his death
is connected

23:22.568 --> 23:24.635
To something he salvaged
from the sea on your behalf.

23:24.637 --> 23:26.504
Man: Our guest tonight
hardly needs an introduction.
I hate this,
i really do.

23:26.506 --> 23:27.805
W--
sir, we need to talk.

23:27.807 --> 23:30.741
Ladies and gentlemen,
isaac monroe.

23:30.743 --> 23:33.210
[ applause ]
i hate public speaking.

23:33.212 --> 23:35.513
Wish me luck.

23:38.618 --> 23:41.552
Why, he's a little
full of himself, huh?

23:41.554 --> 23:44.789
Ladies and gentlemen,
to be honest with you,

23:44.791 --> 23:46.891
I'm not much of an adventurer.

23:46.893 --> 23:49.860
I've been known
to get lost in my own office.

23:49.862 --> 23:51.929
[ laughter ]

23:51.931 --> 23:54.165
I refuse
to sleep in a tent.

23:54.167 --> 23:56.500
Meaning, i'd be useless
on an expedition.

23:56.502 --> 23:58.235
I'm just the money guy,

23:58.237 --> 23:59.870
So instead of me telling you

23:59.872 --> 24:02.706
How much this particular find
means to me,

24:02.708 --> 24:05.910
Allow me to put my money
where my mouth is.

24:07.647 --> 24:09.313
[ audience gasps ]

24:09.315 --> 24:14.151
$7 million in gold recovered
from<i> the empress of africa,</i>

24:14.153 --> 24:16.787
A 19th-century slave ship.

24:19.592 --> 24:21.725
And tonight,
it is my pleasure to announce

24:21.727 --> 24:25.329
That all the proceeds
from this expedition

24:25.331 --> 24:27.698
Will be donated

24:27.700 --> 24:31.235
To the walker institute
for history education.

24:31.237 --> 24:32.670
[ applause ]

24:33.840 --> 24:35.940
Did he just give away
his motive?

24:38.744 --> 24:42.947
I think
he also winked at you.

24:50.056 --> 24:52.756
You lied to us,
mr. Monroe.

24:52.758 --> 24:54.758
You do have a flair
for public speaking.

24:54.760 --> 24:56.527
I said
i didn't like it.

24:56.529 --> 24:58.696
I didn't say
i wasn't any good at it.

24:58.698 --> 25:00.431
I'm gonna have to ask you
to come with me.

25:00.433 --> 25:02.166
So you think
i killed rick rasmussen

25:02.168 --> 25:04.568
For the treasure
i just gave away?

25:04.570 --> 25:05.970
Philanthropy aside,

25:05.972 --> 25:07.838
The gold that you donated
belonged to rick.

25:07.840 --> 25:09.373
It belonged to me

25:09.375 --> 25:11.709
And everything else recovered
from<i> the empress of africa.</i>

25:11.711 --> 25:14.078
He handed the gold over
to you?

25:14.080 --> 25:17.314
That's correct, per my contract
with captain rasmussen.

25:18.651 --> 25:21.118
Dr. Morgan?
Dr. Henry morgan?

25:21.120 --> 25:22.520
That's me.

25:22.522 --> 25:24.655
If this is about
my suit,

25:24.657 --> 25:26.457
I would have dressed properly,
but --

25:26.459 --> 25:28.225
There's a call
for you, sir.

25:30.563 --> 25:32.196
Excuse me.

25:34.667 --> 25:37.001
You still want
to take me in?

25:37.003 --> 25:39.270
Mm, no,
that won't be necessary.

25:39.272 --> 25:42.673
A few hours alone with you
under the lights --

25:42.675 --> 25:44.975
That's more interesting
than this party.

25:44.977 --> 25:47.278
Thank you for your time,
mr. Monroe.

25:47.280 --> 25:48.579
Uh! Hold on.

25:48.581 --> 25:49.880
That came off all wrong.

25:49.882 --> 25:52.716
I was just...Enjoying
our little chat is all.

25:52.718 --> 25:53.984
Sir, i'm working.

25:53.986 --> 25:56.120
And when
you're not working?

25:56.122 --> 25:59.290
I'm a cop.
<i>You</i> are a suspect.

25:59.292 --> 26:01.091
You're thinking twice

26:01.093 --> 26:02.993
About that date with me now,
aren't you?

26:02.995 --> 26:04.061
What date?

26:04.063 --> 26:06.830
That's not an answer.
That's a question.

26:06.832 --> 26:10.067
[ scoffs ]
good night, mr. Monroe.

26:12.338 --> 26:15.272
Night, detective.

26:17.109 --> 26:18.442
Hello?

26:18.444 --> 26:20.978
Adam: I hope you're
enjoying yourself, henry,

26:20.980 --> 26:25.015
Despite being so underdressed
for such an occasion.

26:32.792 --> 26:35.426
What do you want?

26:35.428 --> 26:39.229
To celebrate the discovery
of<i> the empress of africa,</i>

26:39.231 --> 26:41.498
Your ship.

26:41.500 --> 26:43.367
How did you know
i was on --

26:43.369 --> 26:45.069
History fascinates me...

26:46.372 --> 26:48.772
...Especially yours.

26:48.774 --> 26:52.843
Henry morgan, born 1779,

26:52.845 --> 26:54.912
Presumed lost at sea,

26:54.914 --> 26:57.781
<i>Empress of africa,</i> 1814.

26:57.783 --> 27:00.017
Resurfaced 1815.

27:00.019 --> 27:03.053
Committed to an asylum
in the same year.

27:03.055 --> 27:06.190
The ship was your first death,
wasn't it?

27:06.192 --> 27:08.058
Yes.

27:08.060 --> 27:10.427
Mm, i didn't take you
for a slaver.

27:10.429 --> 27:13.697
I wasn't.

27:13.699 --> 27:15.866
I was trying
to free them.

27:15.868 --> 27:19.803
And the weapon
you were killed with?

27:22.341 --> 27:25.009
The captain's flintlock.

27:25.011 --> 27:26.076
Why?

27:26.078 --> 27:29.813
We're looking
for the same thing, henry.

27:31.684 --> 27:33.784
A way out.

27:52.638 --> 27:55.372
It's the same pistol,
isn't it?

27:55.374 --> 27:57.041
[ sighs ] yes.

27:57.043 --> 28:02.012
That pistol is worth more
than all the gold in the world.

28:02.014 --> 28:05.249
[ exhales deeply ]
why?

28:06.652 --> 28:07.985
Why, adam?

28:07.987 --> 28:09.987
[ door opens ]

28:12.458 --> 28:13.824
Henry?

28:15.695 --> 28:17.361
Who were you talking to?

28:21.767 --> 28:23.033
No one.

28:26.238 --> 28:28.372
[ indistinct conversations ]

28:35.748 --> 28:36.947
You can go.

28:36.949 --> 28:39.550
Isaac's alibi
actually checked out.

28:39.552 --> 28:41.919
The guy was giving a speech
at the louvre

28:41.921 --> 28:43.320
The day rick was killed.

28:43.322 --> 28:45.656
Flew back on his g5
that night.

28:45.658 --> 28:46.890
What's he after?

28:46.892 --> 28:49.226
My guess -- you.

28:50.596 --> 28:52.429
Come on, jo.

28:52.431 --> 28:53.664
What are you gonna do?

28:53.666 --> 28:56.233
Are you gonna have dinner
at your desk again?

28:57.203 --> 28:58.402
Go have fun.

28:58.404 --> 29:01.105
You deserve it.

29:04.009 --> 29:06.744
Hey,
got a package for you.

29:06.746 --> 29:09.246
Looks cool.

29:18.257 --> 29:20.424
Nice gun.

29:20.426 --> 29:22.025
Yes.

29:22.027 --> 29:25.262
I, uh, requested it
from the explorer's club.

29:25.264 --> 29:27.631
It was found on the shipwreck
that rick discovered.

29:27.633 --> 29:29.433
I know.
[ chuckles ]

29:29.435 --> 29:30.534
You know?

29:30.536 --> 29:31.668
Yeah, i read it

29:31.670 --> 29:34.538
On your<i> explorer's club journal</i>
here, right?

29:34.540 --> 29:36.573
They did a whole photo spread
and everything.

29:36.575 --> 29:37.808
Kinda cool.

29:37.810 --> 29:38.809
You read my magazines?

29:38.811 --> 29:40.711
Sometimes.

29:40.713 --> 29:42.246
Ah.

29:42.248 --> 29:45.282
Well, thank you, lucas.
That'll be all.

29:45.284 --> 29:47.384
You know, the flintlock pistol
took over a minute to reload,

29:47.386 --> 29:49.253
And its accuracy
was only 15 feet.

29:49.255 --> 29:50.921
Kind of a lame gun,
honestly.

29:50.923 --> 29:52.256
Yes, well,
how interesting.

29:52.258 --> 29:54.224
I mean, how much of a tool
would you have to be

29:54.226 --> 29:55.993
To get shot by that?
[ laughs ]

29:55.995 --> 29:57.361
Right?
You could just duck down

29:57.363 --> 29:59.630
Or, like,
jog away at a moderate pace.

29:59.632 --> 30:01.999
Look, uh, lucas,
i need to be alone.

